                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18230910-280-off1496 t18230910-280-victim2467"></join>
                  </persName>
               
            .</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182309100104"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t18230910-280-person2468">
                  JOHN 
                  PORTER
               <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2468" type="surname" value="PORTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2468" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2468" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am servant to Edward Roberts, <rs id="t18230910-280-viclabel1498" type="occupation">linen-draper</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18230910-280-victim2467 t18230910-280-viclabel1498"></join>. On the 9th of September, between seven and eight o'clock in the evening, the prisoner came to my master's shop. A pane of glass was broken, and the flannel drawn through the glass. Lane alarmed me; I ran out, and, at the corner of Prince's-street, found the prisoner in custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18230910-280-person2469">
                  JOSEPH 
                  LANE
               <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2469" type="surname" value="LANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2469" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18230910-280-person2469" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was near the shop. I live in Queen-street, Oxford-street. I saw the prisoner drawing the flannel through the hole in the window. He ran off. I followed, and saw him stopped; he dropped it immediately.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I met a boy in Oxford-street, who stopped at the shop, and gave the flannel into my hand; half of it being out; he then threw it down, and I picked it up.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18230910-280-verdict1499" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18230910-280-verdict1499" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 15.</p>
